replyContent: Thanks for the feedback Don. It definitely IS a hardware issue. Some devices have terrible audio latency (this is an Android problem in general). My Verizon Galaxy Nexus, for example, plays pretty much real time with my finger taps. But it's going to vary based on device. There is nothing we can do to mitigate this unfortunately.

Update: 1/1/14 I'm probably missing something but I can't figure out seq edit , and when I dl'd Soundcloud to send there to playback SC doesn't recognize the .pat format. ------------------- UPDATE: PLEASE add a share button 11/5/13 This works 10 fold.It really is everything an on the go producer would want plus the sample packs are all great.BUY IT.
replyContent: Hi, to upload to soundcloud is a bit more involved I'm afraid - you first install the SoundCloud app from google Play. Then in Electrum you "export" as WAV. Then in Electrum go Menu->More->Share exported and from there you select the WAV you just exported, and now it should show SoundCloud as an option to share the WAV to.

I play acoustic guitar and was originally looking for just a metronome app; I decided some proper beats would be a lot more useful though. I had a look at some of the more advanced synth / sampler / drum machine apps, but not having the faintest idea how to use rack stuff frankly I might as well have tried to get a beat out of the Space Shuttle. This, however, I got up and running with useful backing in all the time signatures I wanted within 10 minutes. Getting it to swing the way you want it takes some experimenting, but got there in the end!  Gets a 4/5 - it would get a five with just two changes:    [1] Put the BPM control on the main screen and make it a swipe wheel; it's a bit of a pain to try and match speed with how I want to play at the moment - hit menu -> choose BPM -> Click + repeatedly (or type numbers) -> It is not live feedback, so then click Ok -> See if it's the speed I want -> repeat until correct.  [2] Put the shuffle control on the main screen - same reason - the shuffle control at least has instant feed back but navigating through the menus is a bit fiddly.  Even with those two points it's easily worth the money.
